<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-894-804  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 894 804.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Reseller News  Nov 20 1989 n342 p1(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Getting in early on Soviet market.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Hubbard, Holly.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A number of US technology companies are moving to commit time andfunds to marketing within the Soviet Union despite the fact thatno return on investment can be expected for the first few years.andO;Initially there will be minimal revenue to be earned once goodsare exchanged for hard currency.andP;  The long-term reality is thatthe Soviet Union is an emerging market, and decent returns oninvestments could begin to emerge in five to six years.andP;  Companiessuch as Software Products International, CMS Enhancements andAshton-Tate are completing joint venture agreements with variousministries of the Soviet government.andP;  MicroAge and Computerlandboth plan to open stores in the Soviet Union early in 1990.andO;Nantucket is very close to establishing service and supportoperations in Moscow.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Soviet UnionComputer RetailingMarketingInternational TradeMarket EntryForeign InvestmentReturn on Investment.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>